22:35.054 --> 22:38.710
isn't sex our way of saying

22:38.711 --> 22:42.350
"fuck you" to death?

22:44.330 --> 22:47.965
How are you still working here?

22:55.574 --> 22:59.278
<i>The thing was, I started thinking
about it all the time...</i>

22:59.279 --> 23:01.612
<i>my family and death.</i>

23:01.714 --> 23:04.116
<i>Watching me, waiting,</i>

23:04.117 --> 23:08.954
<i>hiding in a closet or parked outside
the house, the</i> Hockey News.

23:10.256 --> 23:13.423
Oh, you might feel some discomfort.

23:15.194 --> 23:17.262
Beautiful day today.

23:17.263 --> 23:20.932
Though I'm stuck in here,
it looked lovely through the window.

23:20.933 --> 23:26.637
And I spoke to your husband.
He explained you were very worried.

23:27.573 --> 23:30.242
He said I was feeling
myself up, right?

23:30.243 --> 23:35.012
Checking, yes. Perfectly
understandable once in a while.

23:36.148 --> 23:38.615
He said once in a while?

24:19.491 --> 24:21.460
Yeah.

24:21.461 --> 24:25.696
Oh, yeah. Keep talking.
Oh, keep talking.

24:30.001 --> 24:34.139
You know, there is a simple check
you can do for testicular cancer.

24:34.140 --> 24:36.274
I heard about this.

24:36.275 --> 24:40.412
Baby, do you want me to check
you now while I'm down there?

24:40.413 --> 24:42.381
- Come on.
- Annie. Annie.

24:42.382 --> 24:45.150
What? Oh, what?

24:45.151 --> 24:50.655
He mentioned that perhaps
you were overly concerned.

24:51.557 --> 24:55.727
I know your family history.
It's very sad.

24:55.728 --> 24:59.965
But that doesn't mean that
you're going to get cancer.

24:59.966 --> 25:05.204
Look, Anne. White coat,
stethoscope. You can trust me.

25:05.205 --> 25:07.339
No more worrying, okay?

25:07.340 --> 25:11.075
- Okay.
- Good. That's my girl.

25:17.549 --> 25:20.852
I don't know about genetics.
I know about computers.

25:20.853 --> 25:24.489
You see, I make these cards, and then I
load them into the front of the computer,

25:24.490 --> 25:27.626
along with everyone else's, and then,
usually the next day sometime,

25:27.627 --> 25:30.128
depending on how many other
people are using the computer,

25:30.129 --> 25:35.333
maybe a few days later, I get
this printout. And there you go.

25:35.334 --> 25:37.936
And for the amount of data
we're going to have, how fast?

25:37.937 --> 25:42.234
The university's mainframe computer weighs
2 1/2 tons. It's capable of storing...

25:42.235 --> 25:45.911
- 700 kilobytes of data.
- I'm sorry. How long?

25:46.813 --> 25:51.350
Once we get the data, make
a program and then load it...

25:52.552 --> 25:54.919
Ten years?

26:00.392 --> 26:02.093
Will?

26:02.094 --> 26:04.463
- Yeah?
- Honey.

26:04.464 --> 26:07.032
Come on. Get up.

26:07.033 --> 26:09.901
- I'm up.
- No, no, no.

26:09.902 --> 26:12.938
If you're not out of
bed, you're not up.

26:12.939 --> 26:14.973
Hey.

26:15.875 --> 26:19.511
- You're not gonna have breakfast?
- Uh... No, I can't.

26:19.512 --> 26:22.613
Work. Got a new client.

26:23.815 --> 26:26.351
They called this morning.

26:26.352 --> 26:30.253
- Kiss?
- I'm already late, Annie.

26:32.491 --> 26:37.962
What? Hey, I'm a musician,
okay? It's a look.

26:39.564 --> 26:41.632
Okay.

26:46.371 --> 26:50.375
When I grow up, I'm gonna
be a pool man, like Dad.

26:50.376 --> 26:54.846
Do you, sweetie? Oh, that's so nice.

26:54.847 --> 26:58.916
Well, maybe when you're a little
older, we'll talk about it, okay?

27:01.019 --> 27:03.621
Mommy's gonna go take a shower.

27:43.094 --> 27:46.830
Mommy loves you, okay?
Have a great day.

28:02.014 --> 28:04.615
All right.

28:04.917 --> 28:07.084
Anne...

28:09.020 --> 28:14.524
your biopsy shows that you have
carcinoma of the left breast.

28:15.360 --> 28:18.663
Phew. And I thought it was
gonna be really bad news.

28:18.664 --> 28:22.300
Well, it's quite
advanced, I'm afraid.

28:22.301 --> 28:26.204
But what I recommend
would be surgery.

28:26.205 --> 28:27.906
- Surgery?
- Mm-hmm.

28:27.907 --> 28:32.377
What's known as a modified
radical mastectomy.

28:33.079 --> 28:36.448
- Oh, God.
- I'm sorry, Anne.

28:36.449 --> 28:42.085
The surgery would require, I'm afraid,
the removal of the entire breast,

28:42.086 --> 28:46.390
as well as most of your
underarm lymph nodes.

28:46.692 --> 28:51.628
Oh, God. Oh, God. William.

28:53.331 --> 28:56.835
I'm scared. I'm really scared.

28:57.937 --> 28:59.604
I don't want to suffer.

28:59.605 --> 29:01.640
- I know. I know.
- I don't want to suffer.

29:01.641 --> 29:04.509
I don't want to die.

29:05.211 --> 29:07.746
Oh, God.

29:08.648 --> 29:10.682
Oh, God.

29:11.584 --> 29:13.684
Oh, God.

29:33.805 --> 29:35.507
Hey.

29:35.508 --> 29:37.775
Hey.

29:43.081 --> 29:45.716
How you doing?

29:47.118 --> 29:50.621
Hey, you want an ice chip?

29:59.531 --> 30:01.565
Oh.

30:06.705 --> 30:09.406
Can I have one?

30:10.675 --> 30:15.347
This is really good ice. Oh, my God.

30:17.249 --> 30:21.219
Oh, my God. Wow. It's really good.

30:21.821 --> 30:25.123
Ow. It hurts. Don't make me laugh.

30:25.124 --> 30:28.525
What? Oh, don't... Oh.

30:36.301 --> 30:39.002
It really hurts.

31:20.044 --> 31:23.448
- And how are we feeling today?
- Not too good.

31:23.449 --> 31:26.983
- Oh?
- I had a breast removed.

31:27.786 --> 31:32.257
- Of course. What I meant...
- I'm feeling all right, considering.

31:32.258 --> 31:34.692
Good.

31:35.094 --> 31:38.730
But, you know, I just knew
this was gonna happen.

31:38.731 --> 31:43.101
It happened to my mom, happened to my
sister, and it happened to my grandma...

31:43.102 --> 31:48.340
Many women feel that way and, yes,
your family did have a bit of bad luck,

31:48.341 --> 31:50.786
- but there are many complex factors...
- It's not bad luck.

31:50.787 --> 31:55.413
There's some evidence that certain
people have a predisposition

31:55.414 --> 31:59.918
- based on diet or environmental factors...
- Excuse me a minute.

32:01.920 --> 32:03.922
What are you doing?

32:03.923 --> 32:06.457
Well, there's just some interesting
current research that suggests...

32:06.458 --> 32:11.062
Look, rejection of orthodoxy always seems
within the purview of the young doctor.

32:11.063 --> 32:12.530
I don't know what my age
has to do with that.

32:12.531 --> 32:15.800
However, to mislead is irresponsible.

32:15.801 --> 32:18.636
There have always been articles.
There always will be articles.

32:18.637 --> 32:22.607
But because some theory is new doesn't
make it right. Proof makes it right.

32:22.608 --> 32:26.845
And I've seen no recent evidence concerning
alternative treatment for cancer

32:26.846 --> 32:29.314
which would lead me to alter
the views I've acquired

32:29.315 --> 32:32.616
over 40 years of practicing medicine.

32:33.618 --> 32:36.553
- I understand.
- Good.

32:39.057 --> 32:41.191
Good.

32:45.363 --> 32:49.534
Hey, if you wanna talk some more,
you can just give me a call.

32:49.535 --> 32:52.737
- Oh, thanks a lot, Dr....
- Doctor!

32:53.439 --> 32:55.773
Sean is fine.

32:55.774 --> 32:58.109
- Anne, right?
- Annie.

32:58.110 --> 33:00.044
Annie.

33:00.045 --> 33:02.146
Thanks.

33:02.748 --> 33:07.118
Let me tell you, I'm gonna be the
best nurse you have ever had.

33:07.119 --> 33:11.922
And I think I already am, because you
can't make out with your other nurses.

34:11.248 --> 34:15.717
Mommy was in the hospital
because Mommy has cancer.

34:16.754 --> 34:20.891
- Didn't Aunt Joan have cancer?
- Yeah, she did, sweetie.

34:20.893 --> 34:23.527
But she died.

34:23.529 --> 34:25.596
Yeah, she did.

34:25.597 --> 34:29.067
- Are you gonna die?
- Hey, no.

34:29.068 --> 34:31.302
I promise you.

34:31.303 --> 34:35.005
You are not gonna lose
your mommy to cancer.

34:35.007 --> 34:37.408
But how do you know?

34:37.409 --> 34:42.012
Because I just know.
I'm not gonna die.

35:14.379 --> 35:16.381
Wait.

35:16.382 --> 35:19.249
I wanna come with you.

35:20.451 --> 35:24.187
- I'm not going anywhere.
- You're going to work.

35:24.756 --> 35:26.457
That's not anywhere.

35:26.458 --> 35:29.227
Aren't you cleaning Louise
and Steve's pool today?

35:29.228 --> 35:33.597
I wanna come with you.
Come on. It'll be fun.

35:34.299 --> 35:36.533
Please?

35:39.237 --> 35:41.705
Come on, then.

35:45.777 --> 35:48.747
- Let's get in.
- Yeah, right.

35:48.748 --> 35:50.215
I'm serious.

35:50.216 --> 35:53.885
- Uh, we're not getting in.
- Why not?

35:53.886 --> 35:56.320
Because I don't want to,

35:56.321 --> 36:01.359
and because I'm a pool man, and pool
men don't get into people's pools.

36:01.360 --> 36:05.528
Is that, like, the pool man's
code of ethics or something?

36:09.467 --> 36:11.535
Why is the water green?

36:11.536 --> 36:16.107
Because Louise's dumbfuck husband
only has me come once a month.

36:16.108 --> 36:19.510
No. No, I mean, really,
why is it green?

36:19.511 --> 36:24.215
Oh, that's... that's algae. It's there
because the pH balance of the pool is off.

36:24.216 --> 36:28.719
It can't be too acid or too base.
It needs to be around 7.5,

36:28.720 --> 36:32.224
the same pH as human tears.

36:32.225 --> 36:34.358
Aw.

36:34.460 --> 36:36.527
See, if you, uh...

36:36.528 --> 36:40.298
If you don't put chlorine in,
you get phosphates,

36:40.299 --> 36:43.000
and algae feeds on phosphate.

36:43.001 --> 36:47.405
But if you put chlorine in,
the algae will die.

36:47.406 --> 36:52.742
But you can't be a dumbfuck and only
have your pool man come once a month.

36:54.379 --> 36:57.248
Are you gonna keep
wearing eye makeup?

36:57.249 --> 37:00.316
Yeah, I am.

37:03.321 --> 37:05.527
I'm gonna get something to drink.
You want something?

37:05.528 --> 37:09.217
Nah. I'll stay here.

37:12.163 --> 37:15.433
<i>I didn't know if the pool was green
because Paul was a bad pool man</i>

37:15.434 --> 37:19.936
<i>or because Louise's husband was
a dumbfuck. But it made me think.</i>

37:25.576 --> 37:28.947
"Breast cancer. See cancer."

37:28.948 --> 37:30.748
Okay.

37:30.749 --> 37:33.751
"Cancer. Any malignant
growth or tumor

37:33.752 --> 37:39.022
caused by abnormal
uncontrolled cell divisions."

37:42.894 --> 37:45.595
William?

37:45.697 --> 37:49.900
- Willy, Mommy needs the bathroom.
- Number one or number two?

37:50.102 --> 37:52.303
Number one or number two?

38:14.458 --> 38:18.997
Mommy's gonna buy you
a new backpack. Okay?

38:23.467 --> 38:25.937
Hi. Sorry. I'm, uh...

38:25.938 --> 38:29.207
- Where are you off to?
- Detroit.

38:29.208 --> 38:33.478
- Gotta run. Hope you're well.
- I am fine. What about our coffee?

38:34.780 --> 38:37.147
You're late.

38:39.050 --> 38:41.485
- What's going on?
- Allen, you got here too late.

38:41.486 --> 38:43.988
- You're late.
- I know, I know. I'm late, I'm late.

38:43.989 --> 38:47.592
We have news. We've identified
a dozen high-risk families...

38:47.593 --> 38:49.494
50-some cancer cases between them.

38:49.495 --> 38:51.596
- Good. And so?
- So?

38:51.597 --> 38:54.332
So now we can begin to look
for correlations in earnest.

38:54.333 --> 38:56.434
We need to interview them,
get blood samples,

38:56.435 --> 38:58.736
extract the DNA, and then
begin to look for markers.

38:58.737 --> 39:01.339
- Okay. "Markers"?
- Genetic markers.

39:01.340 --> 39:05.509
We can track them through the families,
like a signpost on a highway.

39:05.510 --> 39:07.611
Say you have two stretches
of road in the desert...

39:07.612 --> 39:09.863
- And they look exactly the same.
- But if you pass signposts,

39:09.864 --> 39:11.065
you can measure the intervals...

39:11.066 --> 39:12.950
And you can identify the
different stretches of road.

39:12.951 --> 39:14.986
- Even if they look...
- And if those markers

39:14.987 --> 39:19.256
are next to something like the breast
cancer gene, it can be identified.

39:37.975 --> 39:43.046
What is it with the magazine
selection in doctors' offices?

39:43.248 --> 39:45.615
Hello.

39:45.717 --> 39:48.519
<i>Field & Stream?</i>

39:49.221 --> 39:53.957
Do a lot of your patients show
up wearing camouflage bibs,

39:54.359 --> 39:58.296
a bag full of decoys,
and making duck calls?

39:58.297 --> 40:01.064
I don't know, ma'am.

40:01.166 --> 40:04.836
I would think that you would
notice something like that.

40:04.837 --> 40:08.171
Like I said, I don't know.

40:11.375 --> 40:13.977
Quack.

40:16.514 --> 40:18.749
Quack.

40:19.651 --> 40:22.153
Quack.

40:22.154 --> 40:23.788
Quack quack.

40:23.789 --> 40:25.556
Quack.

40:25.557 --> 40:27.724
Quack.

40:29.760 --> 40:31.695
Nice office.

40:32.597 --> 40:37.234
It's not mine. Dr. Benton takes long
lunches. I figure it's not hurting anybody.

40:37.235 --> 40:42.173
It was either here or the cafeteria,
and the floors are much stickier there.

40:42.174 --> 40:44.175
Are you sure you won't
get into any trouble?

40:44.176 --> 40:46.776
I'm a doctor. I can't get in trouble.

40:50.214 --> 40:52.950
What can I tell you?
I'm mostly lab-based,

40:52.951 --> 40:56.921
but I can tell you what I know.

40:57.823 --> 41:00.256
Why do I have cancer?

41:02.093 --> 41:04.161
That's a big question.

41:04.162 --> 41:07.965
There's no one answer.
So many factors involved.

41:07.966 --> 41:11.267
I had a feeling that
you might say that.

41:12.536 --> 41:15.005
You know, I had a teacher
once who told me

41:15.006 --> 41:17.341
what the ideal breast
cancer patient would be.

41:17.342 --> 41:21.746
He said the person with the highest risk
would be a nun living in a cold climate,

41:21.747 --> 41:25.116
who was overweight, who ate
red meat, who was breast fed,

41:25.117 --> 41:27.552
whose mother and sister had
premenopausal breast cancer,

41:27.553 --> 41:30.520
and who was Ashkenazi Jewish.

41:36.127 --> 41:37.628
<i>Not a great start,</i>

41:37.629 --> 41:41.798
<i>but he gave me a pile of books,
and I promised to read them.</i>

41:56.213 --> 41:58.849
Doesn't make any sense.

42:08.826 --> 42:11.562
Oh, shit!

42:12.464 --> 42:14.165
Good, good! Ohh!

42:14.166 --> 42:15.833
<i>...the puck has cleared it behind...</i>

42:15.834 --> 42:18.836
You know, it's been hard for
him, too, with everything.

42:18.837 --> 42:22.440
It's not like he gets...

42:22.441 --> 42:25.176
any attention.

42:25.177 --> 42:27.244
You're right, you know?
I'm being selfish.

42:27.245 --> 42:30.180
No. That's not what I meant.

42:31.082 --> 42:35.486
You're right. Maybe I am.

42:36.388 --> 42:40.725
You know, I feel sorry
for Paul. I do, and I...

42:42.127 --> 42:45.094
I feel sorry for me, too, but...

42:47.798 --> 42:50.300
You know what I feel most of all?

42:52.270 --> 42:54.337
What?

42:56.574 --> 42:59.409
I just wanna be touched.

43:02.079 --> 43:05.615
- Come here.
- Come on.

43:08.285 --> 43:11.220
Come here. Come here.

43:21.632 --> 43:24.268
Okay.

43:24.269 --> 43:26.803
So this is something
we need to look at.

43:29.974 --> 43:32.308
Don't mind me.

43:34.144 --> 43:37.948
So does that mean I have to eat
nothing but grapefruit or something?

43:37.949 --> 43:39.617
No, no. It's nothing that severe.

43:39.618 --> 43:43.187
Although studies have shown that
foods high in fat, fried foods...

43:43.188 --> 43:47.091
- Japanese women.
- Pardon me?

43:47.092 --> 43:50.294
They eat very little red meat,
and they have a much lower rate

43:50.295 --> 43:52.162
of breast cancer than
North American women.

43:52.163 --> 43:54.765
Is that so?

43:55.467 --> 43:57.335
Yeah.

43:59.437 --> 44:01.572
- So did your family go out...
- Three different tests.

44:01.573 --> 44:05.542
One was over ten years.
It's fairly conclusive.

44:08.913 --> 44:11.714
Anyway, I'm gonna get going.

44:17.354 --> 44:20.090
- So...
- We can't know anything.

44:20.091 --> 44:22.126
There's so many possible factors.

44:22.127 --> 44:25.529
It could be diet. It could
be toxins in the home.

44:25.530 --> 44:28.965
One of a thousand viruses
known or unknown.

44:29.267 --> 44:31.602
They know the groups that
have the highest incidents.

44:31.603 --> 44:34.772
They don't know the elements
common to those groups.

44:34.773 --> 44:38.510
We don't know what happened to
your family. We may never know.

44:40.412 --> 44:45.382
My mom used to wrap hot dogs in
bacon, and they deep-fried them.

44:49.453 --> 44:52.723
- What's this?
- It's dinner.

44:52.724 --> 44:55.325
Where's the rest of it?

44:55.527 --> 44:58.928
That's it. It's a salad.

45:01.398 --> 45:04.768
It's got tomatoes in it.
I hate tomatoes.

45:05.270 --> 45:07.871
You can pick them out.

45:11.241 --> 45:14.410
Is everything okay?

45:15.512 --> 45:18.180
Yeah. Yeah.

45:23.120 --> 45:28.290
You know what? Um, I'm gonna
go get us some burgers.

45:29.259 --> 45:30.604
You want one?

45:30.605 --> 45:33.797
Yeah! But no tomatoes
and no oniony things.

45:33.798 --> 45:37.726
No tomatoes and no
oniony things. Okay.

45:37.927 --> 45:40.360
You want one?

45:48.912 --> 45:50.781
Why are we looking
at Mormons and Jews?

45:50.782 --> 45:53.017
Mormons tend to have
very large families,

45:53.018 --> 45:55.653
which makes them excellent
genetic resources.

45:55.654 --> 45:57.421
Plus the Church of Latter Day Saints

45:57.422 --> 46:02.126
believes everyone related to the Mormons
has to be baptized to be saved later.

46:02.127 --> 46:05.262
So, what, there's carcinogens in
the baptismal water they're using?

46:05.263 --> 46:09.867
No. But they keep incredibly detailed
records of their familial ties.

46:09.868 --> 46:15.372
A researcher before us found 30
cases of breast cancer in one family.

46:15.373 --> 46:16.940
Called the Kindred 107.

46:16.941 --> 46:18.976
Ashkenazi Jews are
important, Tom, because

46:18.977 --> 46:21.645
they have an extraordinarily
high rate of breast cancer.

46:21.646 --> 46:25.416
- In New York, it's an epidemic.
- Okay. But...

46:25.417 --> 46:27.317
why couldn't it be the
water or the air?

46:27.318 --> 46:29.887
If that was true, it would be
true of all women in the area.

46:29.888 --> 46:32.189
Breathing the same air,
drinking the same water.

46:32.190 --> 46:34.691
- But it's not.
- So it's something in them.

46:34.692 --> 46:37.093
In their genes.

46:51.842 --> 46:54.611
You're early. Dr. Gold's not here.

46:55.313 --> 46:57.848
So how did you know all
that stuff the other day?

46:57.849 --> 47:01.584
- What stuff?
- The medical stuff.

47:03.954 --> 47:07.565
- I used to be a nurse.
- You used to be a nurse?

47:07.566 --> 47:09.649
- Yep.
- What happened?

47:09.650 --> 47:14.365
What do you mean, "what happened"?
You don't think I enjoy this? Yes?

47:14.366 --> 47:15.966
Okay.

47:15.967 --> 47:19.770
Mr. Elson, you can take your wife
through to the back with the nurse.

